Across the last two semesters we've been hearing the same thing from different parts of the university. Lecturers ask how they're supposed to set AI policy for their own courses when the central guidance is a fifteen-page document few of them have read all the way through. Academic integrity officers see students who often didn't think they were doing anything wrong. Advisors take questions they aren't really equipped to answer. The pattern is consistent: the institution's policy exists, but it doesn't reach students in the moments they actually have to make a choice.
We'd like to commission a small website that addresses that gap — something framed for students rather than written at them. It would sit alongside the formal policy, not replace it, and would aim to give a student a clearer sense of what responsible AI use looks like in their own work. We've been kicking ideas around in committee: scenario walkthroughs, an FAQ of sorts, perhaps something self-check-style where a student can think through whether their planned use of AI feels defensible. We don't have a fixed shape in mind and we'd rather the team building it bring some judgement to that.
Mainly we're thinking of undergraduates as the readers, but we'd be glad if teaching staff also found it useful — something they could point a class to without feeling they were ceding their own role. There's also a quieter group we'd like to keep in view: students who've already been through an integrity process, or who are in group projects where AI use among teammates is contested. Their needs probably aren't the same as a first-year browsing out of curiosity, and we don't want to flatten everyone into one audience.
What we hope to come out of it: fewer students arriving in integrity proceedings because they didn't know where the line sat. Teaching staff with a shared reference they trust enough to recommend. And, more diffusely, less anxiety around the topic on campus — fewer rumours about what's allowed and what isn't.
